nd <strong>b<\/strong> subunits (forming the peripheral stalk). So we have two portions of the molecule the \"static\" <strong>a-b<sub>2<\/sub>-&delta;-&alpha;<sub>3<\/sub>&beta;<sub>3<\/sub><\/strong> part and the rotating <strong>c<sub>10<\/sub>-&gamma;-&epsilon;<\/strong> part. The <strong>&gamma;<\/strong> subunit rotates within the <strong>&alpha;<sub>3<\/sub>&beta;<sub>3<\/sub><\/strong> part of F<sub>1<\/sub> and drives a three-step cycle of conformational changes (via intersubunit interactions) which are linked to the phosphorylation of ADP. <\/p>\n\n<p>There is a useful animation <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ATP_synthase\" rel=\"nofollow\">here<\/a> illustrating the three step catalytic cycle being driven by the rotation of the &gamma; subunit.<\/p>\n\n<p>(image from Aksimentiev <em>et al<\/em>. (2004) \nInsights into the molecular mechanism of rotation in the F<sub>O<\/sub> sector of ATP synthase. Biophys J. 86:1332-44)<\/p>\n","answer_id":7227,"question_id":7226,"up_vote_count":5,"last_edit_date":1361035148}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/7226/cell-respiration-and-oxidative-phosphorylation","last_activity_date":1361035148,"creation_date":1361023223,"answer_count":1,"title":"Cell Respiration and Oxidative Phosphorylation","body":"<p>Why and how does the proton travelling through the stalked particle in the inner mitochondrial membrane, cause a conformational change in the ATPase?<\/p>\n","question_id":7226,"tags":["cell-biology","cellular-respiration","mitochondria"],"score":7,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":114,"up_vote_count":7},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/hpj4v.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":3053,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3053/drosophila","reputation":1073,"display_name":"Drosophila","accept_rate":50},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/VmtoK.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":1320,"link":"http:/