/alan-boyd","reputation":17240,"display_name":"Alan Boyd"},"score":0,"post_id":6903,"edited":false,"creation_date":1360341576,"comment_id":8726,"body":"I think it is incorrect to say that prostaglandins are structurally similar to cholesterol."}],"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1360341533,"creation_date":1358882638,"body":"<p>As I know:<\/p>\n\n<p>One of the most important chemical mediators are prostaglandins that in vivo act on different cell receptors and have different effects on the body. Prostaglandins are twenty-carbon lipid molecules and structurally similar to cholesterol. Prostaglandins have different types, such as F2, E2 alpha, PGI2, and so on.<\/p>\n\n<p>A phospholipase enzyme converts phospholipids of cell membranes into arachidonic acid. The arachidonic acid within the cyclooxygenase enzyme or Cox (both type 1 and 2) can be converted to prostaglandins.<\/p>\n\n<p>PGF2alpha has functions in uterus contraction and bronchoconstriction, so I think both uterus and lung cells produce it.<\/p>\n\n<p>I have no special information about production of PGF2alpha in men.<\/p>\n","answer_id":6903,"question_id":6899,"up_vote_count":2,"last_edit_date":1360341533}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/6899/prostaglandin-f2-alpha-production-in-men","last_activity_date":1360341533,"creation_date":1358875057,"answer_count":2,"title":"Prostaglandin F2-alpha production in men","body":"<p>I am trying to find information on Prostaglandin F2-alpha, specificaly production in men. Could somebody explain how this prostaglandin is produced? What types of cells are producing it, production signaling? Any books on this subject?<\/p>\n","question_id":6899,"tags":["endocrinology"],"score":5,"accepted_answer_id":6903,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":79,"up_vote_count":5},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/vnYni.png?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":1916,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/1916/mysky","