w.gravatar.com/avatar/dbe760221f32f95b2929618a8e23ec84?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":204,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/204/amy","reputation":1824,"display_name":"Amy"},"score":1,"post_id":121,"edited":false,"creation_date":1329772957,"comment_id":1326,"body":"Is anyone still looking for an answer to this? Phenol/chloroform extraction is the gold standard. And here&#39;s a protocol specific to E. coli genomic DNA that doesn&#39;t use phenol/chloroform: <a href=\"http://bio.classes.ucsc.edu/bio105l/EXERCISES/DNA/genomic.pdf\" rel=\"nofollow\">bio.classes.ucsc.edu/bio105l/EXERCISES/DNA/genomic.pdf<\/a>"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/889548c1e8387b3d381853dee5212cfd?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":3632,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/3632/shigeta","reputation":22684,"display_name":"shigeta","accept_rate":86},"score":1,"post_id":121,"edited":false,"creation_date":1329901927,"comment_id":1355,"body":"The answer I got from a colleague is that to PCR from a bacterial sample, you can add bacteria right to the PCR tube without even lysing it.  maybe this so obvious nobody thought to say this...."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/dbe760221f32f95b2929618a8e23ec84?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":204,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/204/amy","reputation":1824,"display_name":"Amy"},"score":1,"post_id":121,"edited":false,"creation_date":1329935425,"comment_id":1369,"body":"@shigeta Oh yeah, I do that often when screening colonies following a ligation/transformation. Stick a colony with a toothpick, stir in some water, use the water for PCR. I increase the first 95C step of a PCR protocol from 2 min to 4 min. These reactions aren&#39;t the cleanest though - if you amplifying a gene for downstream cloning, I&#39;d still recommend purifying the DNA first."}],"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/1a71658d81f8a82a8122050f21bb86d3?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":25,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/25/nick-t","reputation":1720,"display_name":"Nick T","accept_rate":75},"score":7,"is_accepted":false,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/2b005b41b7518c8e7f0c6271857dfa4c?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":177,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/177/jp89","reputation":2007,"display_name":"jp89"},"score":0,"post_id":184,"edited":false,"creation_date":1324400891,"comment_id":251,"body":"To clone a specific gene, you have to design PCR primers that will amplify the gene and also with specific restriction sites flanking your gene. The restriction sites should correspond with the restriction sites found in the poly-linker of your plasmid. For ligation, digest your plasmid, treat with CIP (to reduce vector background), and ligate it with your purified and digested PCR product. Needless to say, this is probably an oversimplified explanation of cloning; let me know if you want more details."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/1a71658d81f8a82a8122050f21bb86d3?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":25,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/25/nick-t","reputation":1720,"display_name":"Nick T","accept_rate":75},"score":0,"post_id":184,"reply_to_user":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/2b005b41b7518c8e7f0c6271857dfa4c?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":177,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/177/jp89","reputation":2007,"display_name":"jp89"},"edited":false,"creation_date":1324402000,"comment_id":252,"body":"@JamesPan I&#39;ve subcloned genes between vectors, I just didn&#39;t know if there was any differences between vector-&gt;vector and genome-&gt;vector.  It&#39;s all DNA so in theory there isn&#39;t anything new, but I don&#39;t know about t