eping makes us feel tired, but <em>why does the disruption of normal sleeping patterns make us feel tired?<\/em><\/p>\n","answer_id":6930,"question_id":6829,"up_vote_count":7}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/6829/why-do-we-feel-tired-if-we-sleep-excessively","last_activity_date":1359167330,"creation_date":1358334464,"answer_count":1,"title":"Why do we feel tired if we sleep excessively?","body":"<p>When we eat, finally we feel full. I know which mechanism causes the sensation of being full. But when we sleep excessively we often still want more sleep. Why does this happen? Is there a mechanism underlying this?<\/p>\n","question_id":6829,"tags":["biochemistry","neuroscience","sleep"],"score":14,"accepted_answer_id":6930,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":755,"up_vote_count":14,"last_edit_date":1358336548},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/s9JpE.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":1809,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/1809/theindependentaquarius","reputation":219,"display_name":"TheIndependentAquarius","accept_rate":40},"comments":[{"owner":{"user_type":"does_not_exist","display_name":"Jay"},"score":1,"post_id":5584,"edited":false,"creation_date":1355482775,"comment_id":8046,"body":"Just to clarify: when you say reboiling, you mean boiling pasteurized milk right?"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/s9JpE.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":1809,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/1809/theindependentaquarius","reputation":219,"display_name":"TheIndependentAquarius","accept_rate":40},"score":0,"post_id":5584,"edited":false,"creation_date":1355483386,"comment_id":8047,"body":"@Jay Yes, I get milk in packets which IS pasteurized. Thanks."},{"owner":{"user_type":"does_not_exist","display_name":"Sobachatina"},"score":2,"post_id":5584,"edited":false,"creation_date":1355496940,"comment_id":8048,"body":"Interesting question. I know that heated milk will separate when it is acidified. Another take on this question would be &quot;Do all harmful bacteria acidify milk?&quot;"},{"owner":{"user_type":"does_not_exist","display_name":"Aaronut"},"score":2,"post_id":5584,"edited":false,"creation_date":1355682633,"comment_id":8049,"body":"@Sobachatina: Even if all bacteria did acidify (which, to a layman in microbiology, sounds like a difficult claim to prove), wouldn&#39;t absence of curdling potentially just mean that whatever bacteria are there have not acidified it <i>enough<\/i> to curdle? So in order to answer &quot;yes&quot; to this question we&#39;d need to not only prove that (a) all harmful bacteria acidify milk, but also (b) that acidification to the point of curdling will take place <i>before<\/i> growth to a harmful degree, and not some time after. Without a mountain of evidence I think it&#39;s easier to just say &quot;no&quot;."},{"owner":{"user_type":"does_not_exist","display_name":"user560"},"score":1,"post_id":5584,"edited":false,"creation_date":1356476504,"comment_id":8051,"body":"Doesn&#39;t separation refer to the fat separating from the water component? When protein is removed, I&#39;ve heard it referred to as denatured or &quot;burnt&quot; or curdled. I would think you can re-pasturize the milk to sterilize it, but if it was previously contaminated, you would not be able to remove bacterial toxins. One toxin that may remain would be endotoxin which causes illness in humans and is only denatured at temperatures in excess of 300&#186;C."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/8729233d525a654914051bf8c1234c78?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":115,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/115/nico","reputation":6011,"display_name":"nico","accept_rate":100},"score":0,"post_id":5584,"edited":false,"creation_date":1356547574,"comment_id":8053,"body":"1) the fact that there are bacteria in the milk (and unless you get <b>sterile<\/b> milk you WILL have bacteria in it) does not mean there are toxins in it (note that sterile is not the same as pasteurized) 2) yes, bacteria will acidify the medium they grow in, as a result of their metabolism (like any other cell would). 3) the milk should not really separate when you boil it, unless you acidify it at the same time (like when making cheese)."}],"answers":[{"owner":{"user_type":"does_not_exist","display_name":"Fladabosco"},"score":1,"is_accepted":false,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/s9JpE.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":1809,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/1809/theindependentaquarius","reputation":219,"display_name":"TheIndependentAquarius","accept_rate":40},"score":0,"post_id":5585,"edited":false,"creation_date":1355673240,"comment_id":8050,"body":"<i>&quot;My suspicion is that you are separating it on purpose,&quot;<\/i> No need to suspect anything. Please read the question again."}],"down_vote_count":1,"last_activity_date":1355673063,"creation_date":1355673063,"body":"<p>Fresh milk does not separate when boiled. I use it in sauces and pan gravies and it always boils and never separates. <\/p>\n\n<p>My suspicion is that you are separating it on purpose, for example to make cheese. In that case you have to add acid or rennet to separate it. If you then re-boil it to separate it again, you get very little solids. I have made cheese at home then tried to 'ricotta' the left over whey and all I get is a tiny bit of solids.<\/p>\n","answer_id":5585,"question_id":5584,"up_vote_count":2}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/5584/if-re-boiling-does-not-curdle-the-milk-can-that-be-taken-as-an-indicator-that-t","migrated_from":{"other_site":{"icon_url":"http://cdn.sstatic.net/Sites/cooking/img/apple-touch-icon.png","audience":"professional and amateur chefs","aliases":["http://seasonedadvice.com"],"favicon_url":"http://cdn.sstatic.net/Sites/cooking/img/favicon.ico","site_type":"main_site","logo_url":"