 fragment between the chromosome and plasmid, and never single :)"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/08613e0b782cdf2bb8f2501cae9bdc5d?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":806,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/806/armatus","reputation":5317,"display_name":"Armatus","accept_rate":81},"score":1,"post_id":6849,"edited":false,"creation_date":1358597944,"comment_id":8362,"body":"good idea on topousomerase though! that might be"},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/08613e0b782cdf2bb8f2501cae9bdc5d?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":806,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/806/armatus","reputation":5317,"display_name":"Armatus","accept_rate":81},"score":0,"post_id":6849,"edited":false,"creation_date":1359019101,"comment_id":8456,"body":"Changed the question to reflect this."},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/08613e0b782cdf2bb8f2501cae9bdc5d?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":806,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/806/armatus","reputation":5317,"display_name":"Armatus","accept_rate":81},"score":0,"post_id":6849,"edited":false,"creation_date":1442928871,"comment_id":65026,"body":"I&#39;m accepting this answer because my understanding has improved in the meantime. As it is not possible to image recombination events as they happen (yet), it isn&#39;t possible to answer this conclusively."}],"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1358586116,"creation_date":1358586116,"body":"<p>Although crossover events can be observed in mitosis (mitotic recombination), they most frequently occur in prophase I of meiosis (crossing over in bivalents). Circular chromosomes are common in prokaryotes, but eukaryotes have linear chromosomes. Remember what meiosis accomplishes and that prokaryotes reproduce asexually. Prokaryotes don't have a need for -- or engage in -- meiotic division, so crossover events in circular chromosomes can really only be observed in instances of mitotic recombination, and I don't know the frequency of this in prokaryotes. <\/p>\n\n<p>In prokaryote DNA replication, if any entangling of the two product circular chromosomes occurs, it is resolved by DNA topoisomerase. So perhaps a crossover would present a similar situation and the cell would resolve it by similar means.<\/p>\n","answer_id":6849,"question_id":2668,"up_vote_count":2}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/2668/do-single-crossovers-occur-in-circular-polynucleotides","last_activity_date":1359019079,"creation_date":1339934780,"answer_count":1,"title":"Do single crossovers occur in circular polynucleotides?","body":"<p>Single crossovers in circular pieces of DNA do not seem to be a big topic, because if they happened, they would lead to a kind of combined chromosome with two inner strands and one large outer strand. (A bit like an 8)<\/p>\n\n<pre><code> ________\n|  ____  |\n| |    | |\n| |____| |\n|  ____  |\n| |    | |\n| |____| |\n|________|\n<\/code><\/pre>\n\n<p>But do these single crossovers actually not <em>occur<\/em>, for example because the crossover machinery is physically not able to do it, or do we just not <em>observe<\/em> them because they will inevitably lead to cell death and/or the chromosome somehow breaking?<\/p>\n","question_id":2668,"tags":["molecular-genetics","plasmids","chromosome"],"score":11,"accepted_answer_id":6849,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":451,"up_vote_count":11,"last_edit_date":1359019079},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/0d0ccebacb6a3a70818fe15f4f5caca6?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":2952,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/2952/user-17670","reputation":93,"display_name":"User 17670"},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/8729233d525a654914051bf8c1234c78?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":115,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/115/nico","reputation":6011,"display_name":"nico","accept_rate":100},"score":1,"post_id":6858,"edited":false,"creation_date":1359012913,"comment_id":8455,"body":"You may want to have a look at: <a href=\"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/371/how-is-temperature-sensed/\" title=\"how is temperature sensed\">biology.stackexchange.com/questions/371/&hellip;<\/a>"}],"answers":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/ec3db653cbc175e2209642ca281f376a?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":1763,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/1763/ben","reputation":678,"display_name":"Ben","accept_rate":75},"score":6,"is_accepted":true,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1358873865,"creation_date":1358873865,"body":"<p>For question 1 it's just a biochemical response from thermoreceptor nerves in the skin, temperatures that are likely to cause lasting damage from prolonged exposure cause a neurological response - in this case it's pain.<\/p>\n\n<p>In address to question 2 it is most likely down to the physiological response of vasoconstriction.<\/p>\n\n<p>When the body is cold the body undergoes constriction of the blood vessels in the extremities to preserve core temperature where it is more essential for the proper functioning of vital organs. By constricting blood flow to the extremities (in this case the hands) there is less volume of blood present, because of this nerves present in the hand are closer to the surface and thus more sensitive to pain.<\/p>\n","answer_id":6898,"question_id":6858,"up_vote_count":6},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/f0a4cefacd2efb730a087a2219fdcfa6?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":2971,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/2971/user2001508","reputation":31,"display_name":"user2001508"},"score":3,"is_accepted":false,"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/kdSRD.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":2972,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/2972/s%e1%b4%9c%ca%80%e1%b4%87s%ca%9c-%e1%b4%80%e1%b4%9b%e1%b4%9b%e1%b4%80","reputation":101,"display_name":"sᴜʀᴇsʜ ᴀᴛᴛᴀ"},"score":0,"post_id":6904,"edited":false,"creation_date":1360258390,"comment_id":8696,"body":"+1  for nice  explanation."}],"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1358883620,"creation_date":1358883620,"body":"<p>It doesn't matter if its hand or any other human body organ, cold would hurt, the reason being that we humans being warm blooded animal require an optimal temperature-pressure balance to be maintained for our nervous system to work in its natural order.<\/p>\n\n<p>So when we have, in your case, cold hands its like a thermal shock to our hand as the above mentioned functional optimality is hampered, and just similar to a hot ceramic cracking due to cold water poured on it, our hand(would not crack, however might in extreme cases) reacts to  this with the sensation termed as Pain.<\/p>\n\n<p>This is a common answer to your questions, cold is directly proportional to pain being felt during our daily engagements(like holding a bag).<\/p>\n\n<p>Pressure plays a vital role in this too as when your hand is cold the pressure exerted to the epidermis is at a reduced rate, which is another reason for the same.<\/p>\n\n<p>Hence commonly my conclusion would be the Temperature-Pressure Factor.<\/p>\n","answer_id":6904,"question_id":6858,"up_vote_count":3},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/3271d15eec2104cadd1cf013eaedebc6?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":2977,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/2977/kim-dyaggnar","reputation":121,"display_name":"Kim Dyaggnar"},"score":2,"is_accepted":false,"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1358978344,"creation_date":1358978344,"body":"<p>It has to do with the way that body parts are more rigid when it is cold. This makes them less flexible and more prone to superficial injury....even without frost nip setting in. In the event that actual frost nip set in, this would be even more sensitive, as you have tiny crystals beginning to form in your cells, like little shards of glass......and, smacking them, rubbing them, or scraping them would be like SMACKING, RUBBING, or SCRAPING your neutral temperature hand against shards of glass. <\/p>\n\n<p>When it is cold, your nerves are very sensitive to the temperature, as it isn\u2019t numb yet, and still....blood flow is slowed down tremendously. In fact, your body has begun \"vaso-constricting\" all blood flow away from your extremities, resulting in nerves being pressed upon by the less supple skin and vascular tissues.<\/p>\n","answer_id":6918,"question_id":6858,"up_vote_count":2}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/6858/why-does-having-cold-hands-hurt","last_activity_date":1358978344,"creation_date":1358628028,"answer_count":3,"title":"Why does having cold hands hurt?","body":"<p><strong>(1)<\/strong>. Why does having cold hands create a painful sensation?<\/p>\n\n<p>Is it a physical effect, maybe a protection mechanism from evolution? <\/p>\n\n<p><strong>(2)<\/strong>. Why, if one's hands are cold, does it feel as if they are more <em>susceptible<\/em> to pain?<\/p>\n\n<p>Note: I have (2) as a separate question because the painful sensation in (1) refers to that from the coldness, whereas in (2), I mean that certain 'ordinary tasks' would feel painful, for example, holding a shopping bag.<\/p>\n","question_id":6858,"tags":["physiology","skin","pain"],"score":8,"accepted_answer_id":6898,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":9265,"up_vote_count":8},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/e0fd6ddc82d922a5d486e878b154f0e0?s=128&d=identicon&r=PG","user_type":"registered","user_id":546,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/546/fragant1996","reputation":56,"display_name":"fragant1996"},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https: