 for, and it looks like this review will give me some more information as to how it works. As a side note, I&#39;m interested in modeling regulatory relationships in time series of expression data, but was curious as to whether, if I could get CNV data for my model as well, if those data could be assumed to be fixed over time, or if that would just have to be a limitation of my approach."}],"down_vote_count":0,"last_activity_date":1358948889,"creation_date":1358948889,"body":"<p>Your question could be phrased more specifically to avoid ambiguity, but rephrasing it the way that I suspect you mean it, (\"Is there any evidence showing that [the rate of] copy number variation changes over time?\"), then yes, there is indeed.<\/p>\n\n<p>The rate depends on many factors including which mechanism and which organism and which region of the organism's genome and as @Michael wrote, also what scale (et. al.) is under consideration too.<\/p>\n\n<p>So your assumption that the rate is static should probably be stated explicitly.<\/p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://dx.doi.org/10.1038/nrg2593\">Nature Reviews Genetics 10, 551-564 (August 2009) | doi:10.1038/nrg2593<\/a><\/p>\n","answer_id":6911,"question_id":6908,"up_vote_count":7}],"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/6908/is-copy-number-variation-dynamic","last_activity_date":1358948889,"creation_date":1358901230,"answer_count":1,"title":"Is copy number variation dynamic?","body":"<p>Is there any evidence showing that copy number variation changes over time? I'm wanting to model interactions in expression level as a dynamic bayesian network, but an assumption my approach will need to make is that it is static.<\/p>\n","question_id":6908,"tags":["bioinformatics","genomics","copy-number-variation"],"score":4,"accepted_answer_id":6911,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":61,"up_vote_count":4},{"owner":{"user_type":"does_not_exist","display_name":"user2968"},"comments":[{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://www.grav