ologist nor a penguin expert, but from all the descriptions and images I could find (even in the same book on other pages!) I think the publishing company is wrong and just too lazy or arrogant to admit this error and too miserly to release a revised version of the book.<\/p>\n\n<p>Who is wrong? Me or <em>Dorling Kindersley<\/em>? Emperor or King?<\/p>\n","question_id":6864,"tags":["species-identification","ornithology"],"score":4,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":true,"view_count":249,"up_vote_count":4,"last_edit_date":1358680161},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/0syJT.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":1813,"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/users/1813/brenton-horne","reputation":1198,"display_name":"Brenton Horne","accept_rate":32},"link":"http://biology.stackexchange.com/questions/6850/what-effect-does-the-endocannabinoid-system-have-on-monoaminergic-neurotransmiss","last_activity_date":1358642146,"creation_date":1358601393,"answer_count":0,"title":"What Effect Does the Endocannabinoid System have on Monoaminergic Neurotransmission?","body":"<p>I know that Δ<sup>9<\/sup>-tetrahydrocannabinol and other cannabinoids increase dopaminergic neurotransmission in the nucleus accumbens and that this is what results in the euphoria experienced by cannabis users. Other than this I do not know what effect cannabinoids have on monoaminergic neurotransmission. I would assume that it increases monoaminergic neurotransmission seeing how rimonabant $-$ a selective CB<sub>1<\/sub> inverse agonist $-$ leads to depression and anxiety which according to the monoamine hypothesis can likely be linked to changes in the activity of monoaminergic pathways in the brain. <\/p>\n","question_id":6850,"tags":["neurotransmitter"],"score":3,"down_vote_count":0,"is_answered":false,"view_count":41,"up_vote_count":3,"last_edit_date":1358642146},{"owner":{"profile_image":"https://i.stack.imgur.com/gv5Fr.jpg?s=128&g=1","user_type":"registered","user_id":1536